240","1230–Female":"1230–Deceased","1235–1293":"1235–1293","1140–1191":"1140–1191","1150–Female":"1150–Deceased","Abt 1230":"about 1230","1235":"1235","before 1179":"before 1179","1230":"1230","1240":"1240","1185":"1185","Abt 1235":"about 1235","1140":"1140","1150":"1150","1293":"1293","1181":"1181","1191":"1191","Ardlamont, Argyll, Scotland":"Argyll, Scotland","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Lamont, Lochow, Argyllshire, Scotland":"Lamont, Argyll, Scotland, United Kingdom","Lamont, Cowal Peninsula, Argyllshire, Scotland.":"Lamont, Argyll, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Glassary, Argyll, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Glassary, Argyll, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lord","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>laford</i>, <i>louerd</i>, <i>lord</i> ‘lord, master’ (Old English <i>hlāford</i>), perhaps given to a someone who played the part of the lord or master of ceremonies in festival games.","Irish: adoption of the English name (see 1 above) as a translation of the main element of Gaelic <b>Ó Tighearnaigh</b> (see   Tierney  ) and <b>Mac Thighearnáin</b> (see   McKiernan  ).","Americanized form of French <b>Laure</b>, a variant of the personal name   Laur   3."],"variants":[{"name":"Tierney","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Eamon, John Patrick, Brigid, Clodagh, Kieran, Michael Sean, Siobhan.","Irish: shortened form of <b>O'Tierney</b>, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Tíghearnaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Tighearnach</i>’, a byname meaning ‘lord, master’. The Gaelic name is sometimes ‘translated’ as English   Lord  . Compare   Tiernan  ."]},{"name":"Lords","meanings":["English: variant of   Lord  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: possibly a metonymic occupational name for a fisherman, from <i>orfe</i>, a species of freshwater fish. Alternatively, a habitational name from Urff near Kassel, formerly Orpha."],"variants":[{"name":"Orff","meanings":["German: variant of   Orf  ."]}]},{"name":"Cowall","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanized form of Polish and Sorbian   Kowal   ‘blacksmith’."],"variants":[{"name":"Kowal","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Jerzy, Kazimierz, Stanislaw, Jaroslaw, Wasyl, Casimir, Danuta, Elzbieta, Ewa, Genowefa, Irena, Jacek.","Polish, Rusyn (from Poland), Sorbian, and Jewish (from Poland): occupational name for a blacksmith, Polish and Lower Sorbian <i>kowal</i>. In North America, this surname may also be a shortened form of any of various derivatives of <i>Kowal</i>, such as Polish   Kowalczuk  . Compare   Koval  .","Americanized form of Rusyn (from Slovakia) and Slovak <b>Kovaľ</b>, Ukrainian, Belorussian, Czech, and Jewish   Koval  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Malcolm","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the medieval Gaelic name <i>Mael Coluim</i> ‘devotee of St Columba’. Columba was a 6th-century monk of Irish origin who played a leading part in the conversion to Christianity of Scotland and northern England;  see also  Callum   and   Colm .  He has always been one of the most popular saints in Scotland, but in the Middle Ages it was felt to be presumptuous to give the names of saints directly to children; instead their blessing was invoked by prefixing the name with <i>mael</i> ‘devotee of’ or <i>gille</i> ‘servant of’. Since the 1930s the given name has been used widely in the English-speaking world, not just by those with Scottish connections."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Malcolm MacFerchar - Lord of Cowall was born in 1181